            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Katarina Petrova\u2019s world has always been one of tangible things: gears, circuits, and the satisfying click of a well-made mechanism. The only child of Bulgarian immigrants who settled in Concord, she was raised on the principles of pragmatism and relentless hard work. Her father, a machinist, would bring home discarded electronics for her to dissect, fostering a deep-seated curiosity about how things worked. This practical upbringing shaped her path, leading her to Cal Poly\u2019s hands-on mechanical engineering program, where she thrived.\n\nHer early career was a swift ascent. After earning her Master's at Stanford while working full-time, she joined a promising hardware startup. This became her defining crucible. For three years, she poured her life into the company, only to see it crumble due to poor market strategy. The failure was a professional and personal blow, coinciding with the end of a long-term relationship. It taught her a bitter but invaluable lesson in resilience and the separation of self from work. She emerged more guarded, but with a sharper understanding of the industry, taking a senior role at an established manufacturing firm. Now, as Director, she leads a team responsible for bringing complex designs to life, a role that perfectly marries her technical acumen and hard-won leadership skills.\n\nToday, Katarina lives a structured life in the Inner Sunset. Her mornings begin with a run through the misty quiet of Golden Gate Park, a necessary ritual before the day's demands. The 8.5-mile drive to the manufacturing facility in South San Francisco is her protected time, filled with engineering podcasts or stoic philosophy audiobooks. Her social circle is small and fiercely loyal, consisting of a few trusted colleagues and a friend from her startup days.\n\nHaving achieved the financial and professional stability her parents dreamed of for her, Katarina now finds herself looking beyond schematics and production schedules. She feels a growing desire for a partnership built on mutual respect, not convenience, and aspires to one day leverage her capital and experience to mentor or invest in young women entering the male-dominated STEM field. She conquered the world of things; now, she\u2019s cautiously beginning to engineer a life with more room for the intangible."
